    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-11-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-11-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="1032"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1032">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">819.011/11–945</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Panama</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hines</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 57</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Panamá</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-11-09">November 9,
                            1945</date>.<lb/>[Received November 15.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Sir: With reference to previous correspondence on the articles of the proposed
                    Constitution relating to the Nationalization of Commerce …</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>As regards Article 219 and other articles of the proposed Constitution relating
                    to the nationalization of wholesale and retail trades, the President assured me
                    that the Panamanian Government has no intention of discriminating against
                    nationals of the United States and that they desire to grant to nationals of the
                    United States the same rights as nationals of Panama. He remarked that the
                    proposed <pb facs="1289" n="1275" xml:id="pg_1275"/> articles of the
                    Constitution are not very clear on this point and that he had instructed the
                    Foreign Minister to study the matter at once and to prepare a formula
                    satisfactory to both governments.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Frank T. Hines</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
